    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one particle instantaneously influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. This connection persists even if the particles are light-years apart. Unlike classical correlation, where two objects might appear related but aren't inherently connected, entangled particles share a unique bond that transcends conventional spatial constraints.\n\nWhen two particles are entangled, their properties are intertwined, meaning the measurement of one particle's property (like spin, polarization, or momentum) will instantly determine the corresponding property of the other particle. This phenomenon puzzled Albert Einstein, who famously referred to it as \"spooky action at a distance,\" because it seemed to violate the principle that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light.\n\nEntanglement challenges our classical understanding of the universe and has profound implications for the foundations of quantum mechanics. It plays a crucial role in emerging technologies like quantum computing, quantum cryptography, and quantum teleportation. Scientists continue to explore and harness the power of entanglement to push the boundaries of what is possible in the realm of quantum physics.",
      "source": "target",
